{{Infobox book | name = Veṇvāroha | title_orig = | translator = [[Malayalam]] commentary by [[Achyuta Pisharati]] (1550–1621) | image = | caption = | author = [[Madhava of Sangamagrama]] (c.1350 – c.1425) | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[India]] | language = [[Sanskrit]] | series = | subject = [[Astronomy]]/[[Mathematics]] | genre = | publisher = Malayalam commentary edited by [[K.V. Sarma]] and printed by Sanskrit College, [[Thrippunithura]], Kerala, India | pub_date = Original in 1403 [[Common Era|CE]]. Malayalam commentary printed in 1956 [[Common Era|CE]]. | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''Veṇvāroha''' is a work in [[Sanskrit]] composed by [[Madhava of Sangamagrama|Mādhava (c.1350 – c.1425) of Sangamagrāma]] the founder of the [[Kerala school of astronomy and mathematics]]. It is a work in 74 verses describing methods for the computation of the true positions of the [[Moon]] at intervals of about half an hour for various days in an [[Moon cycle|anomalistic cycle]]. This work is an elaboration of an earlier and shorter work of Mādhava himself titled ''[[Sphuta-chandrapti|Sphutacandrāpti]]''.<ref name="Pingree">{{cite book|author=David Edwin Pingree|title=Census of the exact sciences in Sanskrit|publisher=[[American Philosophical Society]]|location=Philadelphia|date=1981|volume=4|pages=414 |isbn=0-87169-146-9}}</ref> ''Veṇvāroha'' is the most popular astronomical work of Mādhava.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Helaine Selin|editor-link=Helaine Selin|title=Encyclopaedia of the History of Science, Technology, and Medicine in Non-Westen Cultures |publisher=Springer|date=1997|pages=522|chapter=Article by R.C. Gupta|isbn=978-0-7923-4066-9}}</ref> It is dated 1403 [[Common Era|CE]]. [[Achyuta Pisharati|Acyuta Piṣārati]] (1550–1621), another prominent [[mathematician]]/[[astronomer]] of the [[Kerala school of astronomy and mathematics|Kerala school]], has composed a [[Malayalam]] [[Close reading|commentary]] on ''Veṇvāroha''.<ref name="Pingree"/> This astronomical treatise is of a type generally described as Karaṇa texts in [[India]]. Such works are characterized by the fact that they are compilations of [[algorithm|computational methods]] of [[astronomy|practical astronomy]]. The title ''Veṇvāroha'' literally means [[Bamboo]] Climbing and it is indicative of the computational procedure expounded in the text. The computational scheme is like climbing a bamboo tree, going up and up step by step at measured equal heights.
The novelty and ingenuity of the method attracted the attention of several of the followers of Mādhava and they composed similar texts thereby creating a genre of works in Indian mathematical tradition collectively referred to as ‘veṇvāroha texts’. These include ''Drik-veṇvārohakriya'' of unknown authorship of epoch 1695 and ''Veṇvārohastaka'' of [[Puthumana Somayaji|Putuman Somāyaji]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.new.dli.ernet.in/rawdataupload/upload/insa/INSA_1/20005b5e_1.pdf|author=K.V. Sarma|title=A survey of source materials |publisher=Indian national Academy of Science|accessdate=21 March 2010}}</ref>
In the technical terminology of astronomy, the ingenuity introduced by Mādhava in ''Veṇvāroha'' can be explained thus: Mādhava has endeavored to compute the true [[longitude]] of the Moon by making use of the true motions rather than the epicyclic astronomy of the [[Aryabhata]] tradition. He made use of the anomalistic revolutions for computing the true positions of the [[Moon]] using the successive true daily velocity specified in ''[[Candravakyas|Candravākyas]]'' (Table of Moon-mnemonics) for easy memorization and use.<ref>{{cite journal|author=K. Chandra Hari|title=Computation of the true moon by Madhava of Sangamagrama|journal=Indian Journal of History of Science|volume=38|issue=3|pages=251–253|url=http://www.new.dli.ernet.in/rawdataupload/upload/insa/INSA_1/2000c4df_231.pdf|accessdate=21 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316083104/http://www.new.dli.ernet.in/rawdataupload/upload/insa/INSA_1/2000c4df_231.pdf|archive-date=16 March 2012|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Veṇvāroha has been studied from a modern perspective and the process is explained using the properties of periodic functions.<ref>{{cite journal|author=S. Madhavan|title=Veṇvāroha From a Modern Perspective|journal=Indian Journal of History of Science|volume=47|issue=4|pages=699–717|date=2012|url=http://www.insa.nic.in/writereaddata/UpLoadedFiles/IJHS/Vol47_4_8_SMadhavan.pdf}}</ref>
